    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-05-28T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-05-28T14:00:00-05:00" n="540"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d540">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">662A.00/5–2852: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 540<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Office of the United States High Commissioner for
                            Germany</gloss>, at Bonn</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d540fn1">Repeated to London, Moscow, and Washington; the
                        source text is the copy in Department of State files. Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_AD1">Acheson</persName> was in Paris for the signing of the
                            <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss> Treaty and related documents.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-05-28T20:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 28, 1952—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>924. From Secretary. At tripartite meeting this morning Secretary referred to
                    present and anticipated harassment in Berlin and suggested <gloss
                        target="#t_HICOM1">HICOM</gloss>s be authorized to protest immediately in
                    Berlin without referring back to capitals since protest within few hours should
                    be more effective. If necessary further protests would be made quickly in Moscow
                    but this should be done only under instructions from respective capitals.</p>
                <p>This was agreed and <gloss target="#t_HICOM1">HICOM</gloss>s authorized to make
                    initial protest in Berlin on any further incidents without further
                    authorization.</p>
                <p>It was also agreed lack of legal basis for protest on rupture of communications
                    should not prevent making protest for propaganda purposes. <persName
                        corresp="#p_SR1">Schuman</persName> suggested it describe rupture as
                    peculiar way of encouraging unification and acceptance of Potsdam
                    principles.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
